<br>
I think keys and flags betray the fact that Verant is at a loss how to design the actual zones and dungeons themselves so they are truly evil places in which people will die many many times trying to figure out how tog et to the boss mobs.  Verant has run out of ideas how to make the actual adventuring itself a menacing challenge, so they introduce keys and flags.  <br>
<br>
I've always posted the following solution to the out of whack balance between current guild strength vs encounter difficulty, which is a server wide problem.  Design dungeons and recode the game so that players who die along the way to the encounter cannot be rezzed back into the raid.  They can be rezzed back into raid after the boss is dead, for lewt purposes.  Additionally, the way to the boss mob needs to be locked down after the sequence toward it has been started, so no addtional people can be cothed or corpse summoned in.  In other words: your starting force is all you gonna have to work with, and every death means on less piece of killing/healing/debuffing power available to the raid.<br>
<br>
This would destroy the essential zerg-like tactical advantage that EVERY guild serverwide now enjoys and relies on.  In-raid rezzing is the devil.  In raid cothing is the devil.  In raid corpse summoning is the devil.  If guilds had to relie on near-perfect execution on way to boss mobs, and if deaths mean that many less on your raid force, verant could design dungeons whose sheer difficulty would slow down our consumption of content.<br>
<br>
If this system were already implemented there would be no need for flag or key quests.  But verant fears nerfing the in-raid rez/coth/corpse summon gimpfesting that currently makes it so that even the sloppiest raid can slog their way to the boss mob rezzing merrily on their way and then cothing latecomers etc etc.  <br>
<br>
